<seg id=1> U.S. Confessed Hundreds of Iraqi Civilians Died in Air Attack, British Reporter Said that Bombed was not Military Target at all </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News Agency, Washington, February 13 - U.S. White House confessed on 13th that hundreds of Iraqi civilians were killed when multi-nation air force air-attacked Iraq capital Baghdad, but insisted what they hit was a military target. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> White House spokesman Fitzwalter said that American government deemed this was "indeed a tragic result." </seg>
<seg id=4> But he condemned Iraqi President Saddam for keeping civilians in a military facility and making them in a dangerous situation. </seg>
<seg id=5> He added, U.S. thought that what they hit was a command and control center of Iraqi army. </seg>
<seg id=6> This facility was "painted and camouflaged to evade reconnaissance, but evidence showed this was a military target." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> According to Xinhua News report from London on February 13, Bonne, a reporter of BBC in Iraqi capital Baghdad, confirmed on 13th that no any sign showed the bomb shelter in Baghdad destroyed by American bomber was a military blindage. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Bonne's speech made on BBC TV news rebutted what the American officials claimed that this bomb shelter was a camouflaged military blindage. </seg>
<seg id=9> Bonne once visited this destroyed bomb shelter on-site and found about 400 civilians died. </seg>
</p>
